Description

Adenotonsillectomy. Adenotonsillitis with hypertrophy.
Adenotonsillectomy. Adenotonsillitis with hypertrophy.
The patient is a very nice patient with adenotonsillitis with hypertrophy and obstructive symptoms. Adenotonsillectomy is indicated.
The patient is a very nice patient with adenotonsillitis with hypertrophy and obstructive symptoms.
PREOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS: Adenotonsillitis with hypertrophy.
POSTOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS: Adenotonsillitis with hypertrophy.
OPERATION PERFORMED: Adenotonsillectomy.
INDICATIONS: The patient is a very nice patient with adenotonsillitis with hypertrophy and obstructive symptoms.
INDICATIONS: The patient is a very nice patient with adenotonsillitis with hypertrophy and obstructive symptoms.
Adenotonsillectomy is indicated.
The patient was placed on the operating room table in the supine position.
After adequate general endotracheal anesthesia was administered, table was turned and shoulder roll was placed on the shoulders and face was draped in clean fashion.
The adenoids were removed with suction electrocautery under mere visualization.
The tonsil was removed from the superior and inferior pole using Bovie electrocautery in its entirety in the subcapsular fashion.
The tonsil was removed from the superior and inferior pole using Bovie electrocautery in its entirety in the subcapsular fashion.
The tonsil was removed from the superior pole and inferior pole using Bovie electrocautery in its entirety in the subcapsular fashion.
The inferior, middle and superior pole vessels were further cauterized with suction electrocautery.
There was no further identifiable bleeding at the termination of the procedure.
Copious saline irrigation of the oral cavity was then performed.
The patient was extubated in the operating room, brought to the recovery room in satisfactory condition.
There were no intraoperative complications.
